        <para>
            If you wish to find all material available in a certain path, leave the search term empty and click <guibutton>Search</guibutton>.
            Double-clicking on a folder has the same effect. 
        </para>
        <para>
            If you search for a specific term inside the path you have selected, 
            or make an "empty search" to retrieve all records, 
            you are presented with a list view.  
        </para>
        <para>The format presented in the list view follows <a href="http://www.chicagomanualofstyle.org/home.html" target="_blank">The Chicago Manual of Style</a>. 
           
            If you find that information you have put in is not displayed, please open a <ulink href="http://kjc-sv007.kjc.uni-heidelberg.de/helpdesk/open.php">Ticket</ulink> .</para>
        <para>To the right of the numbering of the item in question, 
            you see the <guibutton>Save Record to My List</guibutton> button <graphic fileref="../themes/default/images/disk.gif" align="center" valign="middle"/>, 
            which allows you to collect the record temporarily in a list accessed from the My List tab <!--We should format tabs in a consistent way (also field labels)--> 
            from which it can be exported. 
            The <guibutton>Save Record to My List</guibutton> button is also present on the detail view.</para>
        <para>In the right corner, you find a graphic representation of the kind of resource the record is about 
            (here "text," represented by <graphic fileref="../themes/default/images/text.png" align="center" valign="middle"/>). 
            Hover over the icon to see its meaning. 
            This icon is also present on the detail view.</para>
        <para>
            If you click on any of the hits in the list, you are taken to the detail view.  
        </para>
        <para>
            <graphic fileref="images/walk-through.07.png" align="center" valign="middle"/>
